There are different ways to tell Jackson how to map the fields of your class to the Json elements. The easiest way is to simply annotate the fields with `@JsonProperty`. If the element name does not match the field name, you can also add a mapped name. e.g.

    @JsonProperty(&quot;my_id&quot;)
    private Long id;

Furthermore, inner classes need to be static.

Your Person class could look like this:

    import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonProperty;

    import java.util.List;

    public class Person {

        @Id
        @GeneratedValue( strategy = GenerationType.AUTO )
        @JsonProperty()
        private Long id;
    
        @JsonProperty
        private String name;
        
        @Embedded
        @JsonProperty
        private List&lt;Information1&gt; Information1;
    
        @Embedded
        @JsonProperty
        private List&lt;Information2&gt; Information2;

        //getters and setters

        @Embeddable
        @Data
        public static class Information1 {

            @Id
            @JsonProperty
            private Long id;
    
            @JsonProperty
            private String name;
    
            @JsonProperty
            private String rating;
    
        }
    
        @Data
        @Embeddable
        public static class Information2 {
    
            @Id
            @JsonProperty
            private long id;
    
            @JsonProperty
            private List&lt;Information&gt; information;
    
            //getter and setters

        }

        @Data
        @Embeddable
        public static class Information {
    
            @Id
            @JsonProperty
            private Long id;
    
            @JsonProperty
            private String key1;
    
            @JsonProperty
            private String key2;
    
            //getters and setters
        }
    
    }

To unmarshall a Json to your Person Object you need a ObjectMapper...

    import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;
    
    ...
        final String json = &quot;&quot;; // &lt;- Your Json, e.g. as a String
        final ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();
        final Person person = mapper.readValue(json, Person.class);
    ...

